es in-depth studies of individual films from different countries including The Birth of a Nation to Nosferatu, and Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves.Medieval film will be of interest to medievalists working in disciplines including literature, history, art history, to scholars working on film and in cultural studies. It will also be of interest to undergraduates, postgraduates and to an informed enthusiast in film or/and medieval culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistorical filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aMiddle Ages in motion pictures. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aMiddle Ages.  aRomanticism.  aauthenticity.  acinematic medievalism.  aextra-diegetically speaking.  afilm noir.  afilm theory.  amedieval art objects.  amedieval films.  autopian realm.1 aBernau, Anke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernau, Anke, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBildhauer, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBildhauer, Bettina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurt, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanim, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHigson, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandy, Marcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Sullivan, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalih, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalker, Alison Tara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter